\section*{Problem Statement}

A spring is used to stop a crate of mass $50\, \text{kg}$ which is sliding on a horizontal surface. The spring has a spring constant $k = 20\, \text{kN/m}$ and is initially in its equilibrium state. In position A, shown in the top diagram, the crate has a velocity of $3.0\, \text{m/s}$. The compression of the spring when the crate is instantaneously at rest (position B in the bottom diagram) is $120\, \text{mm}$.

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(i)] What is the work done by the spring as the crate is brought to a stop?
    \item[(ii)] Write an expression for the work done by friction during the stopping of the crate (in terms of the coefficient of kinetic friction).
    \item[(iii)] Determine the coefficient of friction between the crate and the surface.
    \item[(iv)] What will be the velocity of the crate as it passes again through position A after rebounding off the spring (Fig. 2.14a, b)?
\end{enumerate}

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{fig2_14a.png}
    \caption{Position A and B of the crate with respect to the spring.}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution Outline}

\subsection*{(i) Work Done by the Spring}

The work done by the spring, $W_{\text{spring}}$, can be calculated using the formula for the potential energy stored in a compressed spring:

\[
W_{\text{spring}} = \frac{1}{2} k x^2
\]

where $k = 20\, \text{kN/m} = 20000\, \text{N/m}$ and $x = 120\, \text{mm} = 0.12\, \text{m}$.

\subsection*{(ii) Work Done by Friction}

The work done by friction, $W_{\text{friction}}$, can be expressed as:

\[
W_{\text{friction}} = -\mu_k m g d
\]

where $\mu_k$ is the coefficient of kinetic friction, $m = 50\, \text{kg}$ is the mass of the crate, $g = 9.81\, \text{m/s}^2$ is the acceleration due to gravity, and $d$ is the distance over which the friction acts.

\subsection*{(iii) Coefficient of Friction}

To determine the coefficient of friction, $\mu_k$, we use the energy balance equation considering the initial kinetic energy, work done by the spring, and work done by friction.

\subsection*{(iv) Velocity After Rebounding}

The velocity of the crate as it passes again through position A after rebounding off the spring can be found using conservation of energy principles.

\end{document}
